 alongside him","link_text":"Rev. Daniel Wadsworth"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00453","display_label":"was his wife’s sister and Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth’s grandmother","link_text":"Elizabeth Standley"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00031","display_label":"fathered four children who married four of his own","link_text":"Capt. John Hart"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"I00053","display_label":"Both served as Connecticut Colony Supreme Court judges.","link_text":"Hon. Daniel Edwards"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00089","display_label":"was the cousin whose Indian Neck deed he registered","link_text":"William Hooker"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00263","display_label":"signed a Tunxis dispossession deed as his descendant’s in-law","link_text":"Lt. John Mix"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00439","display_label":"shared his entanglement in Tunxis affairs, decades apart","link_text":"Ezekiel Cowles Jr."},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00045","display_label":"was called with him one of Farmington’s two prominent men","link_text":"Captain Thomas Hart"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM004","plot_notes":"Memento Mori Cemetery, Farmington, Hartford County, Connecticut. Same cemetery as his father Rev. Samuel Hooker (H00007)."},"gender":"male","tags":["politician","judge","compiler_ancestor"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Connecticut Superior Court judge, 1724-1732","primary_url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-john-1664-1746","primary_url_label":"Native Northeast Portal — John Hooker biography"},"documents":["DOC004"],"residence":{"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"law","header":"Judge of Connecticut Colony's Supreme Court","body":"He served as Judge of the Supreme Court of Connecticut Colony from 1724 to 1732 and as Speaker of the Lower House. He also served as witness, certifying Assistant, and Registrar in the 1733 Sue Squa land deed — three official roles in a single transaction."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"He defended Tunxis land rights in court","body":"In 1738, John Hooker provided a formal statement to the Connecticut General Court that ninety acres at Indian Neck had 'always belonged' to the Tunxis tribe — an unusual act of testimony on behalf of the indigenous people whose land his own ancestors had settled near."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"The elm fell so someone could walk straight","body":"His father gave him a site on the west side of Farmington's main street, where he built under the branches of a great elm. The tree became famous through all the region for the company that gathered beneath it — three generations of Hookers lived in its shade before a later owner cut it down to straighten the sidewalk."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"The bell tolled — Hooker stepped out first","body":"A chronicler recorded that every Sunday the bell rang, then began tolling; at the first stroke, Hooker issued from his house and proceeded to the Meeting House. The minister walked from his house. Whoever arrived first waited at the door; together they entered — at which the bell stopped and all the congregation arose."},{"number":5,"category":"character","header":"The Sabbath ended when Hooker touched his gate","body":"The holiness of Sunday was supposed to end at sunset — but no child in the town dared stir until John Hooker gave the signal. When the sun sank, he walked to his gate and leaned on it; open flew the doors and out came the children with a wild rush and shout."},{"number":6,"category":"character","header":"Dark hair, dark eyes — dignity commanding respect","body":"His grandson described him: \"Dark hair and dark eyes, and a dignity in his air and expression that procured profound respect.\" A fine looking man, tall, very erect, and had a 